Fill and boil your kettle, pour the boiling water into a large #saucepan{} on
high heat with @salt{0.5%tsp}. Peel and grate the @garlic{1%clove}(peeled and
grated with a grater) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Halve the @baby plum tomatoes{125} and add them to the #bowl{} with the
@red wine vinegar{2%tsp} and the @olive oil{1%tbsp}. Season with salt and
@ground black pepper{}(to taste), toss and set aside.

Add the @fresh tagliatelle{200%g} to the boiling water and simmer until
tender, ~{4%minutes}. Drain in a #colander{}, pop back in the pan and drizzle
with oil to stop it sticking together.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of oil in a #frying pan{} on medium high heat.

Once hot, lay in the @hake fillet{2} and fry for ~{2%minutes}. Then add the
garlic and a pinch of @red chilli flakes{1%pinch} (careful, they're hot!) and
cook for ~{1%minute}.

Pour in the @olive and caper tomato sauce{1%pot} and @tomato passata{1%cup}
and @water{50%ml}. Season with salt and pepper and a pinch of @sugar{pinch},
and stir together. Bring to the boil, submerge the hake in the sauce and cover
the pan with a #lid{} or some #foil{}. Reduce the heat to medium and simmer
for ~{2%minutes}.

Add the drained pasta to the sauce and toss together, taste and add salt and
pepper if you feel it needs it.

> The fish will break up, but that's the plan so don't worry!

Add the @olives{30} and @wild rocket{40%g} to the dressed tomatoes, toss and
serve on top of the pasta. Sprinkle over a few more @?red chilli flakes{} if
you like things spicy. Enjoy!